How does one determine if the cycle length of the random number
generator X[n] = X[n-c] XOR X[n-d] is maximal (2^c-1 for c>d)?

I found the following maximal-length generators by testing values of 
c and d up to 26 using brute force (O(exp(c))), but that isn't 
practical for pairs like 250, 103 or 1279, 418.

 c   d
(2 - 1)
(3 - 1 2)
(4 - 1 3)
(5 - 2 3)
(6 - 1 5)
(7 - 1 3 4 6)
(9 - 4 5)
(10 - 3 7)
(11 - 2 9)
(15 - 1 4 7 8 11 14)
(17 - 3 5 6 11 12 14)
(18 - 7 11)
(20 - 3 17)
(21 - 2 19)
(22 - 1 21)
(23 - 5 9 14 18)
(25 - 3 7 18 22)

Note that c and d must be relatively prime, but this is not sufficient.  
Also, (c,d) implies (c, c-d).

